hands_on_practices.solution:
We use the explicit matrix forms of the Pauli matrices and compute each square directly via matrix multiplication, using $i^{2}=-1$ and standard matrix product rules.

First, for $\sigma_{x}$:
$$
\sigma_{x}^{2}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
0 & 1 \\
1 & 0
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
0 & 1 \\
1 & 0
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
0\cdot 0 + 1\cdot 1 & 0\cdot 1 + 1\cdot 0 \\
1\cdot 0 + 0\cdot 1 & 1\cdot 1 + 0\cdot 0
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
= I.
$$

Next, for $\sigma_{y}$:
$$
\sigma_{y}^{2}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
0 & -i \\
i & 0
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
0 & -i \\
i & 0
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
0\cdot 0 + (-i)\cdot i & 0\cdot (-i) + (-i)\cdot 0 \\
i\cdot 0 + 0\cdot i & i\cdot (-i) + 0\cdot 0
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
- i^{2} & 0 \\
0 & - i^{2}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
= I,
$$
since $i^{2}=-1$.

Finally, for $\sigma_{z}$:
$$
\sigma_{z}^{2}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
0 & -1
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
0 & -1
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
1\cdot 1 + 0\cdot 0 & 1\cdot 0 + 0\cdot (-1) \\
0\cdot 1 + (-1)\cdot 0 & 0\cdot 0 + (-1)\cdot (-1)
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
= I.
$$

Summing these results,
$$
\hat{\Sigma}^{2} = \sigma_{x}^{2} + \sigma_{y}^{2} + \sigma_{z}^{2} = I + I + I = 3I,
$$
so the proportionality constant is $C=3$.

We are asked to compute the matrix product $\sigma_{z}\sigma_{x}$, where
$$
\sigma_{x} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ 1 & 0 \end{pmatrix}, \quad
\sigma_{y} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & -i \\ i & 0 \end{pmatrix}, \quad
\sigma_{z} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & -1 \end{pmatrix}.
$$
By definition of matrix multiplication, for matrices $A$ and $B$ with compatible dimensions, the product $AB$ has entries $(AB)_{mn} = \sum_{k} A_{mk} B_{kn}$. Applying this to $\sigma_{z}\sigma_{x}$ gives
$$
\sigma_{z}\sigma_{x}
= \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & -1 \end{pmatrix}
  \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ 1 & 0 \end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix}
1\cdot 0 + 0\cdot 1 & 1\cdot 1 + 0\cdot 0 \\
0\cdot 0 + (-1)\cdot 1 & 0\cdot 1 + (-1)\cdot 0
\end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ -1 & 0 \end{pmatrix}.
$$
To identify this with the given options, compute $i\sigma_{y}$:
$$
i\sigma_{y}
= i \begin{pmatrix} 0 & -i \\ i & 0 \end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix} 0 & -i^{2} \\ i^{2} & 0 \end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ -1 & 0 \end{pmatrix},
$$
using $i^{2} = -1$. Therefore $\sigma_{z}\sigma_{x} = i\sigma_{y}$, which corresponds to option C.
